snippet.textDisplay:
I’m 18 right now. But I was 17 (like at the end of last year) I got two of my wisdom teeth out (left side). When my dentist said oh we should get your wisdom teeth out, I was like what. The worst part is that all my wisdom teeth that time are still all under my gums. As in they literally aren’t out yet. But if I left it to grow, they’ll grow and push against my rows of teeth and the dentist recommends that I get it out as soon as possible because there’ll be less swelling if I do it sooner and less painful. I didn’t want to do it but my dad was with me and said just do it.

So we arranged appointments and I got super nervous because I did not want to get sedated. 1) cuz I’ve seen too many wisdom teeth sedated patients 2) I’m scared that I’ll happen to wake up while I’m sedated and 3) I don’t like to be unconscious (I know it doesn’t make sense but I just prefer to be awake I guess).

They explained that they’ll have me awake and that they’ll do two teeth per surgery. So they’ll take out teeth from one side and then do the rest next appointment. BUT, because the teeth were still under the gums, the first tooth they took out took hours to get out. They had to push the gums and take the tooth out in pieces. Fortunately they gave me enough numbing so I didn’t feel a single thing. Except there was a lot of physical PRESSURE. My jaw was tired and I could taste blood but I was overall kind of relaxed. It really wasn’t that bad. But the first tooth took so long that they don’t have time to take out the second tooth. So we arranged a separate appointment for the second one, which was like a month or two later.

So in that time, the tooth actually had time to grow and actually is visible over the gums. So they can just pull it out. Literally that surgery took like 15 minutes with the numbing. And it was SO quick and so painless. And I had no swelling during recovery. (I had swelling for a few days and antibiotics and stitches the first operation) the second operation was so easy and harmless.

Sorry for anyone reading this long long comment. But I just wanna share my experience. I still have both of my right wisdom teeth but they’re still mostly under gums. I also just wanna say that being conscious during surgery isn’t bad but compared to Jaiden, I had it done one at a time. Sorry that you had to go through that Jaiden 😭

snippet.textDisplay:
When I was around 14 years old I had to get two teeth pulled out because I still had ''baby teeth'' and they did that, but then the doctors told me they'd have to cut my gums open, put metal chains in the teeth that were inside my teeth, and pull them with separate brace things in my mouth.


When I went to the surgery thing, they didn't give me that gas thing, they just gave me this blue pill that I think did the same that yours did and it did work on me, but I couldn't drink the pill (because I hate pills and fear them tbh) and drank a LOT of water just to get it down my throat. Then, I was gonna go to the bathroom but it was already time for the surgery so I went anyways and as I was trying to stand up I almost fell, I didn't realize how the pill had already affected me in only 20 minutes after taking it.


During the surgery, I was conscious and saw and heard everything, the dentists/doctors were chill and chatted around and even this other doctor came in and told the others how he's gonna go to this trip. like bro I'm scared as hell here and almost peeing my pants, pls stop making this surgery to take longer than it needs to.


Then it ended, I went to the bathroom to relieve myself aand I don't remember exactly what happened after it but I do remember I couldn't eat food, I could only drink smoothies and soup so that was fun and I had chains coming from my gums for like 2 weeks :') (btw sorry for my bad English)
